2. Lacquer as Protective Skin: Surface Before Subject
Early lacquer technology was fundamentally concerned with preservation. Applied to wood, bamboo, and other organic materials, lacquer formed a dense polymeric membrane capable of resisting moisture infiltration, chemical degradation, and biological attack. In this stage, lacquer functioned as a secondary system — an appendage rather than a structural core. Its role was protective rather than constitutive.
This phase reflects a broader pre-modern ontology in which material hierarchies were clearly defined. Structural integrity resided in the substrate, while surface treatments operated as functional enhancements. The epistemic status of lacquer in this context was instrumental; it extended the lifespan of objects but did not redefine their ontological identity.
However, even in this auxiliary role, lacquer introduced a radical conceptual shift. By demonstrating that surface treatments could significantly alter the temporal stability of objects, lacquer implicitly challenged the assumption that structural essence was confined to core material composition. Preservation itself became a form of material agency.
This insight is crucial for Structural Digitalism. The protective skin stage reveals an early instance in which material processes begin to destabilize the boundary between surface and structure, suggesting that ontological hierarchy is contingent rather than fixed.
